  <static seed="1585" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations25.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{y}{3y-3}-\frac{5}{y-1}}={1}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-6\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{3\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{y}{3y-3}-\frac{5}{y-1}} \amp = {1} \\
  {\frac{y}{3\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)}-\frac{5}{y-1}} \amp = {1} \\
  {\frac{y}{3\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)}\cdot 3\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)-\frac{5}{y-1}\cdot 3\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)} \amp = {3\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)} \\
  {y-15} \amp = {3y-3} \\
  {y-3y} \amp = {-3-\left(-15\right)} \\
  {-2y} \amp = {12} \\
  \frac{{-2y}}{-2} \amp = \frac{{12}}{-2} \\
  y \amp = -6
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp 3y - 3 = 0 \amp \;\amp  y - 1=0 \\
   \amp 3y = 3 \amp \;\amp  y=1 \\
   \amp \frac{3y}{3} = \frac{3}{3} \\
   \amp y = 1 \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>1</m> from the solution set. This value is not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>y=-6</m>.</p>
</solution>
